Project 1: Bringing it All Together

How long does an LED light bulb last?

It depends on the model you use!

Background

How long does the intensity of a single LED light bulb last? For this project, weve obtained LED light bulb #35 using a seed of 40633. The lumens of light bulb #35 are measured 44 times during the duration of 5000 hours (208 days). The goal for this project is to predict the brightness of the bulb as a function of how long its been on.

Data

library(data4led)
bulb <- led_bulb(1,seed = 40633)

library(pander)

The Six Models

The six general models we used were all different and had 1-3 parameters to fill. Function 0 only has one parameter to change. Function 2 only has 2 parameters to change. Functions 2 through 5 have 3 parameters to change.

Function 0 is a constant function.

\[ f_0(x; a_0) = a_0, \quad \text{where } x \geq 0 \]

Function 1 is a linear function.

\[ f_1(x; a_0, a_1) = a_0 + a_1 x, \quad \text{where } x \geq 0 \]

Function 2 is a quadratic function.

\[ f_2(x; a_0, a_1, a_2) = a_0 + a_1 x + a_2 x^2, \quad \text{where } x \geq 0 \]

Function 3 is an exponential decay function.

\[ f_3(x; a_0, a_1, a_2) = a_0 + a_1 e^{-a_2 x}, \quad \text{where } x \geq 0 \]

Function 4 combines a linear term with a logarithmic term.

\[ f_4(x; a_0, a_1, a_2) = a_0 + a_1 x + a_2 \ln(0.005x + 1), \quad \text{where } x \geq 0 \]

Function 5 is a product of a linear function and an exponential decay function.

\[ f_5(x; a_0, a_1, a_2) = (a_0 + a_1 x)e^{-a_2 x}, \quad \text{where } x \geq 0 \]

How I will fit the models

I will fit the models onto the data by making it so the line is within close proximity of the dots.

plot(percent_intensity ~ hours, data = bulb,
     main = "Intensity of Bulb #35 Over 208 Days",
     xlab = "Hours",
     ylab = "Percent Intensity")

Fitted Models

Function 0

\(f_0(0, a_0=100) = 100\)

library(data4led)
bulb <- led_bulb(1,seed = 40633)

t <- bulb$hours
y1 <- bulb$percent_intensity

f0 <- function(x,a0=1){a0 + 0*x}
x <- seq(0,100000,5)
y2 <- f0(x,a0=100)

par(mfrow=c(1,2),mar=c(2.5,2.5,1,0.25))
plot(t,y1,xlab="Hour", ylab="Intensity(%) ", pch=16)
lines(x,y2,col=2)
plot(t,y1,xlab="Hour", ylab="Intensity(%) ", pch=16, xlim = c(0,80000),ylim = c(-10,120))
lines(x,y2,col=2)

With function 0 fitted, the light bulb has an infinite constant power. A super hero might want their hands on this!

This model is inconsistent with the information we know about light bulbs and should not be used.

Function 1

\(f_1(0, a_0=100, a_2=.0009) = 100 + .0009(0) = 100\)

library(data4led)
bulb <- led_bulb(1,seed = 40633)

t <- bulb$hours
y1 <- bulb$percent_intensity

f1 <- function(t, a0, a1) {
  a0 + a1 * t
}
x <- seq(0,100000,5)
y3 <- f1(x,a0=100,a1=.0009) # not a0=100

par(mfrow=c(1,2),mar=c(2.5,2.5,1,0.25))
plot(t,y1,xlab="Hour", ylab="Intensity(%) ", pch=16)
lines(x,y3,col=2)
plot(t,y1,xlab="Hour", ylab="Intensity(%) ", pch=16, xlim = c(0,80000),ylim = c(100,180))
lines(x,y3,col=2)

With function 1 fitted, we can predict the light bulb will get 1% brighter every 1000 hours. This bulb is sure taking its time.

This model is inconsistent with the information we know about light bulbs and should not be used.

Function 2

\(f_2(0, a_0=100, a_1=.0017, a_2=.00000025) = 100 + .0017(0) + .00000025(0)^2 = 100\)

library(data4led)
bulb <- led_bulb(1,seed = 40633)

t <- bulb$hours
y1 <- bulb$percent_intensity

f2 <- function(t, a0, a1, a2) {
  a0 + a1 * t + a2 * t^2
}
x <- seq(0,100000,5)
y4 <- f2(x,a0=100,a1=.0017,a2=-.00000025)
#y4 <- f2(x,a0=100,a1=.00065,a2=.0000001)

par(mfrow=c(1,2),mar=c(2.5,2.5,1,0.25))
plot(t,y1,xlab="Hour", ylab="Intensity(%) ", pch=16)
lines(x,y4,col=2)
plot(t,y1,xlab="Hour", ylab="Intensity(%) ", pch=16, xlim = c(0,40000),ylim = c(-10,105))
lines(x,y4,col=2)

With function 2 fitted, we can expect to replace this bulb in 1.3 years.

This model is consistent with the information we know about light bulbs and might be used.

Function 3

\(f_3(0; a_0 = 99, a_1 = 1, a_2 = 0.0009) = 102.75 + -2.25 e^{-(0.0009) (0)} = 100\)

library(data4led)
bulb <- led_bulb(1,seed = 40633)

t <- bulb$hours
y1 <- bulb$percent_intensity

f3 <- function(t, a0, a1, a2) {
  a0 + a1 * exp(-a2 * t)
}
x <- seq(0,100000,5)
y5 <- f3(x,a0=102.75,a1=-2.75,a2=0.0009)
#y5 <- f3(x,a0=99,a1=1,a2=-.0004) # not a0=100

par(mfrow=c(1,2),mar=c(2.5,2.5,1,0.25))
plot(t,y1,xlab="Hour", ylab="Intensity(%) ", pch=16)
lines(x,y5,col=2)
plot(t,y1,xlab="Hour", ylab="Intensity(%) ", pch=16, xlim = c(0,30000),ylim = c(99,105))
lines(x,y5,col=2)

With function 3 fitted, we can expect this light bulb to burn at a constant rate forever! This would appear to be the perfect bulb.

This model is inconsistent with the information we know about light bulbs and should not be used.

Function 4

\(f_4(0; a_0 = 100, a_1 = 0, a_2 = .93) = 100 + 0(0) + .93\ln(0.005(0) + 1) = 100\)

library(data4led)
bulb <- led_bulb(1,seed = 40633)

t <- bulb$hours
y1 <- bulb$percent_intensity

f4 <- function(t, a0, a1, a2) {
  a0 + a1 * t + a2 * log(0.005 * t + 1)
}
x <- seq(0,100000,5)
#y6 <- f4(x,a0=100,a1=-1.81e-4,a2=0.83)
y6 <- f4(x,a0=100,a1=0,a2=.93) # not a0=100

par(mfrow=c(1,2),mar=c(2.5,2.5,1,0.25))
plot(t,y1,xlab="Hour", ylab="Intensity(%) ", pch=16)
lines(x,y6,col=2)
plot(t,y1,xlab="Hour", ylab="Intensity(%) ", pch=16, xlim = c(0,80000),ylim = c(95,110))
lines(x,y6,col=2)

With function 4 fitted, we can expect rapid growth within the first 2 months but a slight dying increase afterward.

This model is inconsistent with the information we know about light bulbs and should not be used.

Function 5

\(f_5(0; a_0 = 100, a_1 = .01035, a_2 = .00008) = (100 + .01035(0))e^{-.00008t} = 100\)

library(data4led)
bulb <- led_bulb(1,seed = 40633)

t <- bulb$hours
y1 <- bulb$percent_intensity

f5 <- function(t, a0, a1, a2) {
  (a0 + a1 * t) * exp(-a2 * t)
}
x <- seq(0,100000,5)
y7 <- f5(x,a0=100,a1=.01035,a2=.00008) # not a0=100

par(mfrow=c(1,2),mar=c(2.5,2.5,1,0.25))
plot(t,y1,xlab="Hour", ylab="Intensity(%) ", pch=16)
lines(x,y7,col=2)
plot(t,y1,xlab="Hour", ylab="Intensity(%) ", pch=16, xlim = c(0,80000),ylim = c(0,104))
lines(x,y7,col=2)

With function 4 fitted, we can expect a 3% increase within the first 100 days, but the light bulb will have roughly 75% intensity after 2 years. This might be our most realistic model yet!

This model is consistent with the information we know about light bulbs and could be used. Overall, of the 6 functions we used, only functions 2 and 5 display realistic stories of a light bulb. Function 5 might be my favorite because it has a slow decreasing line towards the end of its life.

Project Reflection

Project 1 was quite interesting and Id like to explain the mathematical ideas Ive learned. We created models to ultimately predict the life span of a light bulb. Just because the model fits the data, does NOT mean the model will perfectly predict the story. Like Howard Skipper once said: A model is a lie that helps you see the truth.
